<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="37" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="37">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="37">
This genus includes seven species (
<bibRefCitation pageId="10" pageNumber="37">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
), and one of these has been recorded from Iran (
<bibRefCitation pageId="10" pageNumber="37">Bhatti et al. 2009a</bibRefCitation>
). The genus is included in the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Anaphothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anaphothrips</taxonomicName>
genus-group (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, LA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 76" title="Australian Thripinae of the Anaphothrips genus-group (Thysanoptera), with three new genera and thirty-three new species." volume="2042" year="2009">Mound and Masumoto 2009</bibRefCitation>
), and is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Anaphothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Anaphothrips</taxonomicName>
by having abdominal tergites with median pair of setae (S1) longer than inter-distance (
<bibRefCitation author="zur Strassen, R" journalOrPublisher="Die Tierwelt Deutschlands" pageId="15" pageNumber="42" pagination="1 - 271" title="Die terebranten Thysanopteren Europas und des Mittelmeer-Gebietes." volume="74" year="2003 a">zur Strassen 2003a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
